419. Tabulas non commendaticias sed tributarias. ‘Litterae commendaticiae’ were formal letters of introduction or recommendation, which were constantly given; ‘litterae tributariae’ is a phrase coined by Cicero to suggest that the communications which Metellus received from Verres offered him some substantial consideration if he would try to quash the charges against him. Cicero had mentioned previously that Metellus at his first coming to Sicily had taken a strong line against Verres, but after a while, on the receipt of certain letters from Verres, had entirely changed his policy, and did everything to hinder the prosecution. It might be trans- lated perhaps ‘ letters, not of introduction, but of credit.'
